    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm not sure about a soil test right now though. i just want to know if it's definitely nitrogen. i noticed the soil looks pretty depleted and it feels like something is just stripping the nutrients away really fast. is there anything else that could be \"stealing\" the nitrogen from the plant?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the yellowing of lower leaves is the classic sign of nitrogen deficiency, other factors like heavy root competition from weeds or excessive watering can also deplete soil nitrogen rapidly. It is also worth noting that some pests, like spider mites or leaf miners, can damage foliage and mimic nutrient issues, though they usually cause speckling rather than uniform yellowing. To address this without a test, applying an organic nitrogen booster like compost tea or blood meal directly to the soil around the base of the plant should help replenish what is being stripped away. Remember that if the plants were recently moved to heavy clay or sandy soil, they may simply need time to develop a stronger root system to access these nutrients efficiently.",
